Running a targeted samplefile fit at NERSC
==========================================

Use this workflow to fit a specific set of objects supplied as a FITS file.
The samplefile is broadcast to all MPI ranks; each rank processes its assigned
healpix files and fits only the targets listed in the sample.  Per-file versus
per-object parallelism is chosen automatically based on average targets per
healpix file.

Files used
----------
  etc/fastspecfit-env.sh          module loads and environment variables
  etc/fastspecfit-sample.sh       srun wrapper called by the .slurm script
  etc/fastspecfit-sample.slurm    editable Slurm job template

Samplefile format
-----------------
A FITS table with at minimum these columns:

  SURVEY    (str)   e.g. main, sv3
  PROGRAM   (str)   e.g. dark, bright
  HEALPIX   (int)   nside=64 nested HEALPix pixel
  TARGETID  (int64) DESI target identifier

Add a Z (float64) column if you want to supply input redshifts and will pass
--input-redshifts.

Step 1 — set up the environment
-------------------------------
On a login node or in an interactive session:

  source etc/fastspecfit-env.sh [fastspecfit_version]

Set OUTDIR_DATA if the default ($PSCRATCH/fastspecfit/data) is not suitable:

  export OUTDIR_DATA=/path/to/output

Step 2 — estimate resources
---------------------------
Count how many unique healpix pixels the sample touches and how many targets
each contains — this determines MPI rank utilization:

  python - <<'EOF'
  import fitsio, numpy as np
  t = fitsio.read('my-sample.fits', columns=['HEALPIX', 'TARGETID'])
  pix, counts = np.unique(t['HEALPIX'], return_counts=True)
  print(f'{len(t):,d} targets across {len(pix):,d} healpix pixels')
  print(f'avg {counts.mean():.1f} targets/pixel, max {counts.max()}')
  EOF

  Rule of thumb: use enough nodes so each rank processes ~1 healpix file.
  If avg targets/pixel < mp, per-file parallelism is auto-selected
  (each worker handles one healpix file); otherwise workers share each file.

Step 3 — edit the Slurm template
--------------------------------
Copy and edit etc/fastspecfit-sample.slurm:

  cp etc/fastspecfit-sample.slurm ./fastspec-loa-mysample.slurm
  $EDITOR fastspec-loa-mysample.slurm

Variables to set at the top of the script:

  N               number of nodes (update --nodes in #SBATCH too)
  mp              multiprocessing workers per MPI rank
  specprod        spectroscopic production (e.g. loa)
  samplefile      absolute path to the sample FITS file
  stage           fastspec (default) or fastphot
  input_redshifts set to 'true' to use the Z column from the samplefile

The script includes a single-rank Numba warm-up step before the full srun,
so no separate cache pre-population is required.

Step 4 — submit
---------------
  sbatch fastspec-loa-mysample.slurm

Step 4a — review runtimes (optional)
------------------------------------
After jobs complete, parse the log files to review per-healpix timing
statistics and check for unexpected failures:

  parse-fast-logs $OUTDIR_DATA/loa

Use --pattern to restrict to a specific production or stage, e.g.:

  parse-fast-logs $OUTDIR_DATA/loa --pattern "fastspec-loa-*.log"

The output reports per-file object counts and mean/median/P10/P90 timing for
fitting, I/O, and per-object throughput.  These numbers are useful for
diagnosing slow healpix pixels and refining node/time estimates for future runs.

Step 5 — merge output
---------------------
After the job completes, merge the per-healpix output files:

  mpi-fastspecfit --specprod loa --mp=16 \
      --samplefile my-sample.fits \
      --merge --merge-suffix mysample \
      --outdir-data $OUTDIR_DATA

Node / worker arithmetic (Perlmutter CPU, 128 physical cores per node)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  MPI ranks per node   = 128 / mp
  Total MPI ranks      = 128 * nodes / mp
  cpus-per-task        = mp * 2  (hyperthreading)
  Effective workers    = 128 * nodes  (all cores busy)

Empirical throughput (loa, sv3, --mp=16):
  dark targets:   ~8 s/obj/core  (~10 obj/min/core)
  bright targets: ~11 s/obj/core (~5 obj/min/core)
